        <name>38.1.2.1 Basic Mean and Variance</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p class="HELM_exercise"&gt;Exercise&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;For a random variable \(X\) with the following probability distribution function&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;\( f(x) = \begin{cases} \dfrac{x}{@a@} &amp;amp; \text{if $0 \leq x \leq {@b@} $} \\ 0 &amp;amp; \text{elsewhere} \end{cases}, \)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;calculate the mean and variance of \(X\).&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;\( \text{E}(X) = \) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;\( \text{V}(X) = \) [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]] [[feedback:prt2]]&lt;/p&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;h4 class="HELM_solution"&gt;Solution&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;p&gt;To calculate the mean of \(X\) we do the following&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;\[\begin{align*} \text{E}(X) &amp;amp;= \displaystyle{\int_0^{{@b@}}} x \times \dfrac{x}{{@a@}&amp;nbsp;} \; dx \\ &amp;amp;=&amp;nbsp;\int_0^{{@b@}} {@f@} \; dx \\&amp;amp; = \left.\dfrac{x^3}{3 \times {@a@}} \right|_0^{{@b@}}\\&amp;amp;={@ta1@}. \end{align*}\]&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;To calculate the variance of \(X\) we use the formula \( \text{V}(X)=\text{E}(X^2) - \text{E}(X)^2\). We have that&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;\[\begin{align*}\text{E}(X^2) &amp;amp;=&amp;nbsp;\displaystyle{\int_0^{{@b@}}} x^2 \times \dfrac{x}{{@a@}&amp;nbsp;}\; dx \\&amp;amp;=&amp;nbsp;\int_0^{{@b@}} {@g@} \; dx\\&amp;amp; = \left.\dfrac{x^4}{4\times{@a@}} \right|_0^{{@b@}} \\&amp;amp;=&amp;nbsp; {@h@}. \end{align*}\]&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Thus, we have that&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;\( \text{V}(X) = \text{E}(X^2) - \text{E}(X)^2 ={@h@} - ({@ta1@})^2&amp;nbsp;=\displaystyle{{@ta2@}}. \)&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</generalfeedback>
